sexuality, and what is known of Maimonides' client population. A final chapter discusses Maimonides and Freud, noting that many distinctive features of the cure of souls are shared by Freud's original formulation of psychoanalysis. Indeed, the many points of convergence suggest Freud's direct or indirect contact with Maimonides' legacy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aJudaism and psychoanalysis. 0aMeditationxJudaism. 0aProphecyxJudaism. 0aPsychotherapyxReligious aspectsxJudaism. 0aSoulxJudaism. 4aJewish Studies : Jewish Philosophy. 4aJewish Studies : Judaica. 4aPsychology : Psychology of Religion. 4aPsychology : Psychology. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / Theology.2bisacsh1 aMerkur, Dan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWeiss, David S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438427447423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438427447/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles